fields.title: New Yorker for a Day
fields.subtitle: Something in the air of NYC renders sleep utterly useless
fields.author: Mary-Anne
fields.story: Now you may call us crazy, most of the time I‚Äôd disagree with you and simply say we have an adventurous streak. However‚Ä¶ on this occasion I may just agree with you! I‚Äôm a massive Hugh Jackman fan. Greatest Showman - yes! Wolverine - yes! Les Mis - yes!! This may seem like an unrelated point but hang in there. Following the amazing international success of The Greatest Showman, Mr Jackman arranged a world tour aptly named: The Man, The Music, The Show. I just had to get tickets. Well a number of circumstances meant that Hugh and I never managed to be in the same continent at the same time. I shall try not to take it personally‚Ä¶ After deciding that this was an opportunity not to be missed, we booked tickets - in New York.  The concert was on a Saturday. We found some super flights, leaving Friday night and arriving home Sunday night. We blackmailed booked in the grandparents as babysitters and smoothed things over with work. It was a tight squeeze but Hugh wasn‚Äôt going to escape this one. After logistics we were left with ONE day in NYC and we planned to make it epic. The flight passed quickly in a blur of gins and Margaret Atwood‚Äôs epic sequel to the Haidmaid‚Äôs Tale - The Testaments (recommendation alert). We‚Äôd booked the Hilton New York JFK Airport Hotel for convenience and following an age getting through US border and customs, undertook a little custom of our own. Christening our US arrival with a pint(ish) of Bud Lite in the hotel bar. We woke to a crisp but sunshiny ‚Äòfall‚Äô morning full of excitement for Hugh Jackman, sorry, the day ahead. It was bagels and black coffee for brekkie, then a yellow taxi into the ‚ÄòBig Apple‚Äô. First stop was the Empire State Building. After finally finding our way in, getting through security and handing over all the $$$$ we were delivered to the rooftop in a beautiful art deco style elevator. There was lots of information about the building‚Äôs history and construction but, full-disclosure, we headed straight for the view. What a day for it! We saw so far, the view-finders all work and the scene was just stunning. You could even see the Statue of Liberty herself. We video called the kids, who totally didn‚Äôt care and got SO MANY photos. Realising time was quickly passing we headed out on foot. No end destination in mind, just lapping up all the excitement this iconic city had to offer us. We wandered past the New York Public Library and into Grand Central Station, somehow finding ourselves in the landmark Apple store. After dragging Mark out, we happened across a market where we fuelled up with street food and more coffee. Note: Barbecued corn on the cob with lemon juice, salt and cayenne pepper is a game-changer. The next pinch-me moment was getting to Trump Tower! An imitator out front wearing a trump face mask totally had me fooled üòÇ. We passed on the Trump Bar, the Trump Grill, the Trump Caf√©, the Official Trump Merchandise Store and no kidding, the Trump Ice-Cream Parlour for the wonders of Central Park. The green space and free musical events were a wonderful antidote to the hustle of the city centre. With Hugh time quickly approaching, we headed back into the city, grabbed a ‚Äòslice‚Äô for dinner from one of the renowned Ray‚Äôs Pizzas places and a drink from the Hard Rock Cafe in Times Square - If you‚Äôve never had a blackberry sangria, you‚Äôre missing out. Taxi back to the hotel for an outfit change and what can I say??It was. simply put. The. Greatest. Show!

fields.title: Canada/US Road Trip
fields.subtitle: Nothing but open road ahead
fields.author: Adam
fields.story: Part 1 - This trip has to have been my biggest missions yet. 10,000 miles across Canada and the US in my pickup truck. I started with a focused and determined attitude, despite my tight budget. I filled my tank with fuel and set my tripmeter. I filled my backseats up with beer, water and instant noodles. With no real plan, a suuuper tight budget and a broken neck (another crazy story), my trip options could have been limited but honestly, the world was my oyster. I set off North West from Vancouver towards Alaska. On my way I saw beautiful scenery - lakes, waterfalls and mountains all from the relative comfort of my truck. I didn't really know why I was going to Alaska or even what was there. Someone just told me it was a nice place. Just outside of Whistler, I saw a lady, asleep on the side of the road. We were in bear country and it was late at night. I only just saw her in the darkness. I wasn't even sure if it was a person but I decided to turn the truck around and pull over. At first inspection I couldn't tell whether i‚Äùd found a man or a woman. All I knew was that this person was cold and tired - weather beaten I suppose. I don't remember her name now but I do remember the rather elaborate story of how she ended up in her situation. I was left thinking: "I can't leave this woman here. It's cold and the bears could get her. But can I trust her?" She didn‚Äôt seem the athletic type and despite my fractured vertebrae, I had a can of bear spray, I knew I could handle anything that comes up. So she got in my truck. She had a lot of stories. I discovered she had a similar back condition as me and that she‚Äôd left a motorised wheelchair around her friend's house. Fortunately, her and her friend live on the route I was travelling. She asked if I‚Äôd help her pick up the wheelchair from her friend's house. I, of course, agreed to help. What I didn't realise until we got there was that I‚Äôd find myself lifting the windows out of a retirement home to give her access inside! She dives in through the window I‚Äôm holding open, jumps on an electric wheelchair and comes crashing back out the house. I‚Äôm not sure if she's ever ridden this thing before. Next, I found myself strapping this wheelchair down in the back of my pickup. Driving away slowly, I wondered is this really her wheelchair or have I just helped this woman rob an old person's home? Overall, I concluded that she was a lovely if crazy woman. So grateful for all the help I bestowed upon her - buying me coffee at every stop and fuelling up the truck. Along our journey together she narrated more of her life story. I found myself relating as we'd both gone through similar experiences. She‚Äôd had such a rollercoaster of a life with a tremendous amount of bad luck that had brought her to her current situation. I realised as I dropped her off and continued on my road trip that she was like an older version of me. Part 2 - As I started driving the Stewart-Cassiar Highway. I stopped at a service station with a really cool toilet. The toilet was inside a stunning log cabin with carefully crafted logs and I found this fascinating in itself. At the same service station, I met a couple of bikers who were also traveling the country. We spoke for ages about an app for bikers they‚Äôve have been promoting. It was a Lonely Planet style app specifically for bikers that tells you about the best routes, places to see and what to do in various places. I shared with them how I traveled from Vancouver to Whistler onto Kamloops. They told me the best part of Alaska was in Hyder and that it wasn't worth driving the extra 5000 kilometres to get to Fairbanks. He did warn me however that he‚Äôd spotted bears along the way. Without any expectations for Hyder, I took a ninety degree turn and took his word for it. Not long after leaving the service station, I saw a black bear on the side of the road casually finding its way to the woods. Seeing the bear filled me with confidence as it was somehow confirmation the man I had met randomly was truthful. Along the way I took a four hour detour, driving through a bear sanctuary where all the Salmon swam upstream. The smell was particularly nasty as not all the salmon make it upstream, some of them die. It was survival of the fittest and so was named ‚ÄòThe Fish Creek Ecosystem‚Äô. I was told there was a glacier just a couple miles down the road. I started taking photos from the start of the view of the glacier. I couldn‚Äôt decide when to stop so I kept taking photos at every possible opportunity as the view was stunning and just kept on changing. When I eventually reached the top, the view was breathtaking - it was surreal. I took a few photos, sat down and enjoyed a couple of beers with my view until the sunset. A lovely German couple lent me their binoculars so I could get a magnified view of the glaciers with my camera. Morning came, I watched the sunrise and the clouds came in. The clouds majestically covering the glacier slowly until the view was obscured. That prompted me to spread my wings and move on to the next destination.
